body.value: Yes. Kyle, will you please introduce yourself, sir.
Um, barely.
Barely.
I can see him, yeah.
He can do whatever.
We just going to have a conversation. It ain't all theater coordinated.
That would be interesting. That would be good stuff happening.
Okay.
So I know that only ... How long have you had the company now?
And ... So the first people ... Did you start it at SUNY?

And how did you ... I think you and I may have talked about this a little bit, like ... SUNY Purchase is where I wanted to go to school, but they didn't give me enough money, right? So I went to Utah. But how, what was ... How did you end up at SUNY Purchase? You say that's where you got the bulk of your dance training.
But like was dancing in your family?
Did you grow up in D.C.?
Yeah.
And what is the work that you're interested in?
No, I like it when you move your arms.
But I don't want to wash him out either, you know?
Okay.
You said you were at Morgan State.
So what were like your influences then growing up? You know, I know we're both sort of in the hip hop era. I mean, what made you say, "You know, I wanna do this dance thing"? Like who does that?
I did not know that you played the cello.
When was ... When?
Yup. Did you do a piece with live cello like not that long ago? Did you-
Yeah.
What was it like to work with Wendy Whelan?
How would you describe your process?
I'm gonna go back a little bit. It feels like a ... Would you say you have a strong relationship to music?
So in our work, how did you land on Nina?
Do we have a title for this piece?
I wouldn't even worry about it.

So one of the questions I have is about ... What does it mean to get ... What does it mean to have gotten the MacArthur? Were you like one of the, either the youngest, or one of the youngest people to ever get it?

I think there's something that I know as a choreographer that I don't think people always realize ... You know, like this is gonna be shown to folks mostly in the know, you know? And then as it starts to get out to part of the digital archive, I think it's still gonna be folks who love dance or are interested in dance or have an interest in black choreographers and their trajectory. But I don't think people often realize ... At least I know it wasn't until a certain point in my own career that I was like, "Oh, like the self-doubt is real." Like the journey of ... It's like the next grant and the next project and the next and is this, you know, and how is this, what is this project going to be? And is it ... It seems like that would be an interesting, like you were describing that relationship of getting the MacArthur ... Talking about that full-circle. How do you keep yourself grounded in that? Like what did it take to make that circle? And do you still deal with like, wow, like maybe this isn't a good piece? Or what does it mean for something to be good enough for you?
What solo was that tour?
Was that with Joyous?
ND?
Where did we stop? Where did we leave off?
Oh, doubt, yep.
Who do you talk to about your work? Like who do you like to get feedback?

What, what, so you ... We recently ... [inaudible 00:26:54] And over the past 15 years, I've asked this question about black dance. And I feel like that question has shifted in terms of what it means. I don't think people are asking that question in the same way people were talking about that before. So I guess this is a two-part question. One, is there something called "black dance"? And, if so, what would that be? And then second: how do you think conversations around blackness and performance and even just identity have shifted in the past 50 years?
What role do you feel artists have in that? And what role does it play in your work?
Um-

Yeah, what role does art ... So, you know, part of what we were talking about was how people are now with expressing their blackness and black bodies on stage, or in black bodies. And so I was wondering what role do you feel that artists play? Sort of like the conversation, the moment we're in right now with identity and blackness and, you know, whatever else. Some of the things that have really come to forefront. What role do you really feel like the artist played? And then that was the other part: what role do you feel like that plays in your work? But the other part of the question.
Just a ... How long were you with Dorfman and how long were you with Bill T?

Last two questions. And you kind of touched on this before, so this is just another opportunity to perhaps ask and answer this question. Who or what are other strong influences? Maybe in life or in art or in your dance community.
Great.
And the last thing: what does a perfect day look like?
When is your next day off?
Cool. Shit.
Just a couple months.
All right. That's all I have. Do you feel like there's anything ... Do you have any questions for me or even like about this project? Like why say yes to this project? Why ...
No. I think a lot of these questions have to do with it.

You know, the project is turning to a legacy project. You know, I always feel like choreographies from different black choreographers, but I didn't think of it as a thing, I was like, "There's just some people I wanted to work with." And then next thing I know, 10 choreographers-
